english:
  title: A Gift for Chen, the Court Official
  author: Cao Shu
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A Korean subject, cast far into exile,
    Year after year passes, yet return remains distant.
    Cold garments and sparse rice—each day a struggle,
    The heart grows heavy, bones ache, strength wanes away.

    Have you not seen? When gold in the purse runs dry,
    Even heroes and great men lose their luster.
    The divine dragon, though trapped in muddy depths,
    Without clouds cannot ascend to heaven's heights.

    Have you not witnessed? Spring's glory comes but once—
    Do not squander your youth in vain.
    Now the season turns fair, the weather smiles,
    Peach and plum blossoms flush red, willows drape in green.

    Yet thinking of it all brings only sighs,
    For home lies beyond mountains and distant waters.
    Wherever I wander, who mourns the lost?
    All I meet are strangers from other lands.

    I blame no man, I curse not Heaven,
    Yet alas, in these twilight years, fortune grows thin.
    Do not lament that success comes not early—
    The Emperor is wise, and you are still young.
    Wealth and glory each come in their season;
    Do not embitter your heart and waste your days in aging.
    Do not trade joy for sorrow's sake alone.
  footnotes:
    - The poem is addressed to Chen, likely an official or friend of the poet who also faced hardship and exile.
    - The divine dragon metaphor references a classical image of latent talent unable to manifest without proper circumstances.
    - The references to peach and plum blossoms and willow trees evoke the beauty of spring and the transience of youth.
